    <name>
      <text>Classifying a given number as odd, even, prime or composite</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>
During a mathematics lesson, Grade 10 students were asked to classify the number
<strong>{@num@}</strong>.
</p>

<p>
Which of the following statements are true? Select all that apply.


[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]] </p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p><strong>Worked Solution</strong></p>

<p>Given the number: <strong>{@num@}</strong></p>

<hr>

<p><strong>1. Testing whether the number is even or odd</strong></p>

<p>
A number is <strong>even</strong> if it is divisible by 2, and <strong>odd</strong> if it is not.
An easy way to check this is to look at the last digit.
</p>

<p>
{@if is_even
  then sconcat(
    "The last digit is ", mod(num,10),
    ". Since this digit is even, the number is <strong>even</strong>."
  )
  else sconcat(
    "The last digit is ", mod(num,10),
    ". Since this digit is odd, the number is <strong>odd</strong>."
  )
@}
</p>

<hr>

<p><strong>2. Testing whether the number is prime or composite</strong></p>

<p>
A number is <strong>prime</strong> if it has exactly two positive divisors: 1 and itself.
It is <strong>composite</strong> if it has more than two positive divisors.
</p>

<p>
{@if num = 1
  then "The number 1 is neither prime nor composite."
  else if is_prime_num
    then sconcat(
      "After checking divisibility up to ",
      floor(sqrt(num)),
      ", no divisors other than 1 and itself were found. ",
      "Therefore, the number is <strong>prime</strong>."
    )
    else
      sconcat(
        "The number has a divisor other than 1 and itself, ",
        "so it is <strong>composite</strong>."
      )
@}
</p>

<hr>

<p><strong>Final classification:</strong> You  need to choose: </p>
<p>one option describing whether the number is even or odd, and in this case; {@if is_even then "<li>It is even</li>" else "<li>It is odd</li>"@}
</p>
<p>one option describing whether the number is prime or composite. Therefore;</p>
{@if is_prime_num then "<li>It is prime</li>" else "<li>It is composite</li>"@}
</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
